fields.name: Guaymas Basin Heat Flow Data from IODP Expedition 385

fields.value: This dataset contains heat flow measurements from eight sites drilled in the Guaymas Basin, Gulf of California, during the International Ocean Discovery Program (IODP) Expedition 385. The data provide insights into the thermal regime of the basin, including conductive and advective heat transport associated with magmatic sill intrusions. Heat flow values range from 119 to 221 mW/m� in sedimentary basin sites and from 257 to 1003 mW/m� at the Ringvent sill intrusion. The dataset includes sedimentation-corrected heat flow estimates, thermal conductivity measurements, and modeled heat dissipation rates. These data support the interpretation of heat transport mechanisms in young rift basins and contribute to understanding crustal cooling timescales, hydrothermal circulation, and the thermal evolution of sediment-filled rift systems.

The heat flow data in this dataset were collected from eight drilling sites in the Guaymas Basin, Gulf of California, during IODP Expedition 385. In-situ temperature measurements were obtained using downhole temperature probes, and thermal gradients were calculated from multiple depth profiles at each site. To determine sediment thermal properties, core samples were analyzed using needle probe and half-space methods to measure thermal conductivity. These measurements were then combined to estimate heat flow values across the basin.

To account for the influence of rapid sedimentation on heat flow, sedimentation rate corrections were applied. The dataset includes heat flow values ranging from 119 to 221 mW/m� in sedimentary basin sites and from 257 to 1003 mW/m� at the Ringvent sill intrusion. Analytical and numerical models were used to evaluate the contributions of conductive and advective heat transport. At Ringvent, hydrothermal circulation was inferred from estimated fluid discharge velocities between 10 and 200 mm/yr, with possible recharge sites identified approximately 1 km from the sill�s border.

Transient thermal models were also applied to estimate the cooling rates of sill intrusions and their contribution to regional heat flow. These models suggest multiple timescales of cooling, including rapid cooling of recent sills and long-term thermal evolution of the basin floor. The dataset provides valuable insights into the thermal processes governing young rift basins and contributes to a better understanding of heat transport in sediment-filled, tectonically active environments.

The dataset follows the standardized format of the Global Heat Flow Database, ensuring compatibility with existing heat flow records. It is structured as a tabular dataset with fields for site location (latitude, longitude, and water depth), measurement type (borehole, probe, or laboratory-derived), thermal conductivity values, geothermal gradients, and calculated heat flow estimates. Metadata fields include data quality indicators, sedimentation rate corrections, and references to the original study.

fields.name: International Heat Flow Commission
fields.description: The International Heat Flow Commission (IHFC) is a specialized body within the International Association of Seismology and Physics of the Earth's Interior (IASPEI). It plays a pivotal role in advancing geothermal research by promoting the collection, standardization, and dissemination of heat flow data. The IHFC oversees the maintenance and development of the Global Heat Flow Database, ensuring its accuracy, accessibility, and scientific integrity. By fostering international collaboration and providing guidelines for data acquisition and reporting, the IHFC supports studies on Earth's thermal regime, contributing to broader geoscientific research and practical applications in energy and environmental fields.

fields.name: Global Heat Flow Database
fields.description: The Global Heat Flow Database is a comprehensive collection of geothermal heat flow measurements from around the world. It serves as a critical resource for understanding the Earth's thermal structure and processes, contributing to studies in geodynamics, plate tectonics, and climate history. The database aggregates data from scientific publications, including terrestrial and marine heat flow measurements, offering insights into variations in heat flux across different geological settings. Managed collaboratively by institutions and researchers, it aims to support global research and applications in Earth sciences, energy exploration, and environmental studies.

fields.title: Heat flow and thermal regime in the Guaymas Basin, Gulf of California: Estimates of conductive and advective heat transport

item.title: Heat flow and thermal regime in the Guaymas Basin, Gulf of California: Estimates of conductive and advective heat transport
item.abstract: Abstract Heat flow is estimated at eight sites drilled int the Guaymas Basin, Gulf of California, during the International Ocean Discovery Program Expedition 385. The expedition sought to understand the thermal regime of the basin and heat transfer between off-axis sills intruding the organic-rich sediments of the Guaymas Basin, and the basin floor. The distinct sedimentation rates, active tectonics, and magmatism make the basin interesting for scientific discoveries. Results show that sedimentation corrected heat flow values range 119�221 mW/m2 in the basin and 257�1003 mW/m2 at the site of a young sill intrusion, denominated Ringvent. Thermal analysis shows that heat in the Guaymas Basin is being dissipated by conduction for plate ages >0.2 Ma, whereas younger plate ages are in a state of transient cooling by both conduction and advection. Drilling sites show that Ringvent is an active sill being cooled down slowly by circulating fluids with discharge velocities of 10�200 mm/yr. Possible recharge sites are located ca. 1 km away from the sill's border. Modelling of the heat output at Ringvent indicates a sill thickness of ca. 240 m. A simple order-of-magnitude model predicts that relatively small amounts of magma are needed to account for the elevated heat flow in non-volcanic, sediment-filled rifts like the central and northern Gulf of California in which heating of the upper crust is achieved via advection by sill emplacement and hydrothermal circulation. Multiple timescales of cooling control the crustal, chemical and biological evolution of the Guaymas Basin. Here, we recognize at least four timescales: the time interval between intrusions (ca. 103 yr), the thermal relaxation time of sills (ca. 104 yr), the characteristic cooling time of the sediments (ca. 105 yr), and the cooling of the entire crust at geologic timescales.
